{"author":"Joe Oakhart","author_email":"joeoakhart+bot@navapbc.com","author_id":"594c-9dcf-5ad6-4e6d","data":{"fields":{"description":"## Why\n\nReview-result sidecars are pruned to the most recent `RETAIN_PER_TICKET` per ticket. Two problems:\n(1) the plan-review cap is only 10 (`src/rebar/llm/plan_review/sidecar.py:43`), too shallow for an\naudit trail; (2) `src/rebar/llm/code_review/sidecar.py` has **no `prune()` and no\n`RETAIN_PER_TICKET`** — its `emit()` only calls `append_event`, so code-review sidecars grow\n**unbounded** today (a latent bug). A ticket reviewed many times loses (or never bounds) its history.\n\n## What\n\nRaise the review-sidecar cap to 50 as a **single shared constant** and give code review a prune path:\n\n1. In `src/rebar/llm/plan_review/sidecar.py`, set `RETAIN_PER_TICKET = 50` (the one definition site\n   for review-sidecar retention).\n2. In `src/rebar/llm/code_review/sidecar.py`, `from rebar.llm.plan_review.sidecar import\n   RETAIN_PER_TICKET` (import the SAME object — not a mirrored literal), add a `prune(ticket_id, *,\n   repo_root=None)` mirroring `plan_review/sidecar.prune` (same newest-first git-rm logic, same\n   best-effort/exception-swallowed posture, filtering on its `-REVIEW_RESULT.json` suffix), and call\n   it best-effort at the end of `emit()` after `append_event`.\n\nRetention constants for OTHER sidecars (`completion_sidecar.py`, `overlap/digest_sidecar.py`) are\nindependent policies and are **out of scope** — this story governs only the two review sidecars.\n\n## Approach rationale\n\n50 is a bounded increase chosen to cover realistic remediation-loop depth (observed re-review series\nare single-digit rounds) while still capping growth of `REVIEW_RESULT` events on the tickets branch.\nImporting one constant (rather than mirroring a literal) makes \"one cap\" literally true by object\nidentity and avoids config-surface proliferation (no consumer needs a per-repo override — YAGNI).\nPlan-review sidecars are emitted on the WORK ticket and code-review sidecars on the code-review\nARTIFACT ticket (`target_ticket=artifact_id`) — disjoint ticket directories — so a per-directory,\nsuffix-filtered prune only ever sees its own review type despite both sharing `EVENT_TYPE =\n\"REVIEW_RESULT\"`. `prune` resolves `RETAIN_PER_TICKET` from the module global **inside the function\nbody at call time** (not as a default-argument value, which Python binds once at definition), so the\nactive cap is always the current constant.\n\n## Compatibility & rollback\n\nPure bound increase + a new (previously absent) code-review prune. No schema/format change. Already-\npruned/over-grown history is not retroactively changed. Reverting to 10 prunes more aggressively on\nthe next write; removing the code-review prune restores unbounded growth. No migration.\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n\n- [ ] `RETAIN_PER_TICKET == 50` and `code_review.sidecar.RETAIN_PER_TICKET is\n      plan_review.sidecar.RETAIN_PER_TICKET` (the code-review module imports the SAME object — one\n      definition site for review-sidecar retention). Oracle: a unit test asserting the value and the\n      `is`-identity.\n- [ ] Appending 51 `REVIEW_RESULT` events to one code-review artifact ticket leaves exactly 50\n      retained (newest kept) — i.e. code-review sidecars are now pruned (they were not before).\n      Oracle: an integration test appending 51 synthetic events via the real `emit` path and asserting\n      the retained count is 50 and the newest survive.\n- [ ] The same holds for plan-review sidecars at the new cap of 50. Oracle: the analogous\n      integration test on a work ticket.\n- [ ] `make lint && make typecheck && make test` pass."}},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"EDIT","timestamp":1784081187883748001,"uuid":"1ee8096c-b874-4e0a-a80e-059bbaf68592"}